<document>
	<title>A screening tool to detect psychosocial adjustment of children with
   cystic fibrosis.</title>

	<author>Rodgers-B.</author>
	<author>Ferholt-J.</author>
	<author>Cooper-C-L.</author>

	<source>Nurs-Res. 1974 Sep-Oct. 23(5). P 420-5.</source>

	<abstract>A tool to assess psychosocial adjustment of school-age children with
   cystic fibrosis was developed using three instruments: a
   standardized open-ended parent interview, a self-administered
   teacher questionnaire, and a self-administered parent demographic
   data form.  The three instruments enabled the pediatric nurse
   practitioner to make a clinical assessment of the child&apos;s
   psychosocial adjustment.  This assessment was then checked for
   validity by means of a social worker interview.  Implications for
   further research are discussed.</abstract>

